Live Band Karaoke with THE LOST WEEkENDs was exceptionally fun! The band are VERY talented musicians and they work hard to give each guest singer a good experience. The crowd at the IVY ROOM was very supportive (and forgiving!) and the staff was enthusiastic,and charming as usual. Aside from the live band part, it differed from regular karaoke in that the lyrics you are reading do not alert you to a starting point where you should start singing. They ARE on an Ipad, but its pretty much just the same as holding a piece of paper with lyrics printed on it. I suggest going to the bands website, finding the link to their list of Karaoke covers and practicing a little with a YouTube karaoke video of that song beforehand-if you dont know the song you want to perform really well already. I cant wait to go back, I hope the LosT WeeKends return to The Ivy Room soon !

Quite possibly my favorite music venue. Ive been going to shows for 40 years and, for the last 30 years, Ive been in just about every venue in the Bay Area to see bands and AS the band. As an audience member, and as a musician, the sound quality is never what it could be. Sometimes its the shape of the room, sometimes its the equipment, most of the time its the person running the board. The Ivy room has GREAT SOUND. Luck? Talent? Engineering? Who cares why? It is the only place that hasnt made me want to commandeer control of the board. How do they do it? It remains a mystery that I dont need to solve. Hardcore, metal, country, R&B (Ive only seen loud bands there) my money says any band is going to sound great at The Ivy Room.

Oh, man, this place rocks!  From the door manager to the bar staff and everyone in between, it is welcoming, friendly, and absolutely fabulous as a gig venue.  They have a very small stage, and a four-person band barely has room to move around, yet the action is close to the crowd and mesmerising.  The acoustics are great, the ambiance is warm and cozy.  There isnt much seating, just one large booth in the back.  Bathrooms were clean, well stocked.  They literally let people hang out and talk until they were locking the doors.  The guests and artists intermingled after the show which was great, and we got to chat with bay area notables that we havent seen in ages.  Seriously, I feel like the show I saw on 3/12/22 was one of the best gigs I have ever attended, and the cloud-nine feeling still is with me two days later.  I loved going to the Ivy Room.  In fact, just the name made me think it was an old-school type of place, and indeed it is.  The Ivy Room opened in 1943 in the middle of World War II.  The original neon sign is still on the building.   You can picture sailors and soldiers on leave, filling the place with laughter and hearing music.  There are multiple restaurants nearby for a delicious dinner.  We went to the White Lotus across the street, Thai food, and had a fabulous experience there.  The Ivy Room is now on my Top 10 places to see a band!

This is best for intimate shows, because there isnt a lot of room, but for a small room the acoustics are excellent! We saw hed P.E. and there were maybe 50 people at the show. I believe the band thought the place was bigger but they did the gig anyway. I called ahead to ask about disabled seating and they said let them know at the door. I had a chair at a table for the whole night. Doing gigs at small places like this is a gift to the local fan base. The tickets were ridiculously cheap, but different shows charge differently. I wasnt thrilled about going with the hubby because I wasnt a huge fan like he is. But, after that show, I came away with a satisfied grin because you could sit 20 feet away from the stage and understand every lyric. The 2 warm up groups were also good. It reminded me of the 90s when places like The Omni and The Stone got decent names but tickets were reasonable. I would go to another show there if given the opportunity.

I would never usually give any place that few Stars, and it really isnt do to whether or not it was a good musical venue ( and I was there to watch a show) but, it gets this Love rating because the fact that it couldnt accommodate me as a person with physical disabilities. The entire concert area was basically an open floor with about 7 chairs lined up against the far wall. the website says that, if you call them beforehand, they can make accommodations and reserve a space for you. I attempted to call the venue no less than four times within a two-week period to attempt to reserve a space. Each time I found that their voice mail was completely full and I was hung up on (via the system) because I couldnt leave a message and at no point did an actual human being ever pick up. Therefore, I was forced to take a chance and hope that there would be a space or at least a chair for me the evening of the show. I know now that if I hadnt been the first person to arrive for that show there would not have been a space for me at all. I ended up having to stand on that chair for the entire duration of the concert I attended and paid for. The show was great but the venue was awful
